REVIEWS AND BOOK NOTES 
Siemens's account of the Basin's eighteenth century (chapter 5) is based largely on the writings (and map mak­ing) of a military engineer, Miguel Corral. These are the first maps of the area with recognizable, modern con­ventions. Mountainous relief, rivers, other shaded topog­raphy and vegetation provide improvements to seventeenth-century renditions that lacked consistent ori­entation, scale, and other references. By this time, how­ever, "ethnocentricity has virtually erased Indian toponymy. . . ." Military considerations predominated and the secrecy guarding Spain's possessions permeates the accounts. Ranching, the enduring motif of the Gulf Coast, flourished. 
The nineteenth century was the geographical era of Alexander Von Humbolt in Mexico. The Gulf Coast had its own German geographer and naturalist, Carl Sarto­rius, who spent most of his life in the region and gener­ated an account (Mexico, Landscapes and Popular Sketches, English edition 1961, original German, 1859) relevant to the San Juan Basin. Sartorius painted a roman­tic picture that emphasized verticality. The vegetation and climate change in bands as one ascends from the Port towards the highlands. He documents the variety of agri­cultural products in Veracruz but the inhabitants of the region are seen as lazy and the potential of the land never realized. He suggests German colonization but that never really materializes. Siemens spends a lot of time with Sar­torius (Chapter 6). He deals with the biases and insights of this naturalist whose detailed work gives a valuable picture of an economy that at times seems harsh but also hints at abundance and ease. The Veracruz natives were calledjarochos, and by now the blacks and Indians have all but vanished from the picture we receive. Meanwhile, ranching, that enduring Gulf Coast motif, continued to flourish. 
Chapter 7 takes us into the modern era. An irrigation project during the presidency of Mexico's Miguel Ale­man (1946-1952) brought an army of government engi­neers to the San Juan Basin who measured everything hydrological, made maps, and sang the praises of central planning. They shunned the disorder of "traditional" sub­sistence and recommended mechanization, drainage of the wetlands, and crop improvement. Their intervention (wetland drainage and a canal system that eventually encircles the Basin) sought to reverse the ecology that permitted the wetland cultivation some 1,500 years ear­lier. Their model of development was imported from the temperate world and ultimately failed. But they began a process of data collection that greatly enhanced Siemens's own early Gulf Coast research and later doc­umentation of the ancient wetland features. Cattle ranch­ing, now featuring the humped Zebu-Swiss hybrid, is still doing quite well today. 
This volume is a fascinating historical read for any­
one familiar with Mexico's Gulf Coast and a compelling 
document for those interested in research on ancient agri­culture in the tropical lowlands. Siemens's prose is a bit thick at times but he more than makes up for that with his insightful diagnosis of changing perspectives and biases as well as his own positive approach to the bounty and potential of the Gulf Coastal landscape that has been so long obscured by postconquest history. I highly rec­ommend it for archaeologists, historians, geographers, and other scholars looking for an excruciatingly detailed contrast to the high, the dry, or the ancient Maya. 
