Reviewed by Harry Iceland, Florida Atlantic University. 
The "Clovis First" model for the peopling of the New World is in the process of being overturned as current research-discoveries in the field, laboratory analyses of old and new finds, and emboldened efforts at reinterpre­tation of the data-point to earlier and more complex pat­terns of migration. This timely synthesis of the archaeological evidence will help scholars, students, and the knowledgeable public make more sense of the unfold­ing debate. The author's focus is on western North Amer­ica, but his systematic, concise reviews of findings at principal early sites, organized chronologically and regionally, are hemispheric in scope and he makes a deter­mined effort to make technical terminology understand­able to all readers. His interpretative conclusions concerning the likely importance of marine routes and cul­tural adaptations in the earliest, pre-Clovis, migrations are convincing, although admittedly still speculative. 
Dixon begins with a useful review of Paleoindian 
archaeology and the hard-won acceptance, beginning in 
the late 1920s, of an Ice Age colonization of the New 
World, followed by a brief discussion of migration mod­
els. He then examines the evidence for pre-Clovis (i.e., 
pre-11,500 B.P.) occupations at 26 sites in the U.S. and 
Canada and then at 17 sites in Mexico and Central and 
South America. In two summary tables, he evaluates the 
evidence for each site against established criteria for pre­
Clovis status, concluding that a handful of sites in North 
and South America fulfill all criteria and others seem 
likely, based on the preponderance of evidence, to have 
been occupied before 11,500 B.P. 
